TRICHINELLOSIS - GERMANY: WILD BOAR MEAT
****************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 3 Apr 2013
From: Edoardo Pozio <edoardo.pozio@iss.it> and Karsten Nockler <karsten.noeckler@bfr.bund.de> [edited]


Trichinella-infected sausages made with pork from a hunted wild boar have been placed on the market in Saxony (Germany). The products, a raw-fermented sausage containing boar meat and boar meat roast, have been sold in the German federal states of Saxony and in the south of Brandenburg by a company's fleet of mobile market vendors.

The area where the products were distributed borders Poland and the Czech Republic. According to a health alert from the Ministry of Saxony, the roast ("Wildschweinbraten") and the sausages ("Wildschweinknacker") were sold on 26-27 Mar 2013, and the roast also on 23 Mar 2013.

More information can be found on the RKI website:
http://www.rki.de/DE/Content/InfAZ/T/Trichinellose/Trichinenbelastetes_Wildschweinfleisch_03_2013.html.

So far, no cases of trichinellosis have been observed. Given the variable incubation period (5-45 days) and the shelf life of the sausages, we would like to know about any trichinellosis cases with a symptom onset between the end of March 2013 and the end of June 2013 with a travel history to the affected area.

The contact person at the RKI is Dr. Faber (<faberm@rki.de>;
+49 30 18754 3533).

